@article{Barton:1986fk,
	Abstract = {Suppose that selection acts at one or more loci to maintain genetic differences between hybridising populations. Then, the flow of alleles at a neutral marker locus which is linked to these selected loci will be impeded. We define and calculate measures of the barrier to gene flow between two distinct demes, and across a continuous habitat. In both cases, we find that in order for gene flow to be significantly reduced over much of the genome, hybrids must be substantially less fit, and the number of genes involved in building the barrier must be so large that the majority of other genes become closely linked to some locus which is under selection. This conclusion is not greatly affected by the pattern of epistasis, or the position of the marker locus along the chromosome.},
	Annote = {Introduction

- Recapitulation of previous results for simpler cases by Bengtsson (1974, 1985) and Spirito et al. (1983) who considered gene flow between two discrete demes, and by Barton (1979) and Petry (1983), who considered flow through a continuous habitat [island model in the case of Petry]. The general conclusion is that a single genetic difference can only present a substantial barrier to gene flow of those genes which are so tightly linked to the selected locus that selection is much stronger than the rate of recombination. It is therefore unlikely that a single-locus barrier could trigger the divergence of a new species through its effect on gene flow as suggested by White (1968, 1978) in his "stasipatric" model.

- Local adaptation or speciation may often involve many genes under selection. This situation has been studied by Barton (1983) and Barton and Hewitt (1983) for a continuous habitat, assuming multiplicative fitnesses. Indeed, they found that selection on a large number of linked loci gives a stronger barrier than when the same selection pressure is concentrated on a single locus.

- The goal of BB1986 is to extend the studies above with multiple selected loci. In particular, they attempt to define the "effective migration rate" between genetically distinct popoulations, and the "strength" of genetic barriers in such a way that these terms can be used consistently across a variety of models.

Definitions

- A general concept of "gene flow" is encouraged. The flux is defined as the change in frequency of a given allele in a given population due to migration, deltau = m Deltau. Here, u is the allele frequency and Deltau is the differenc in allele frequencies between the focal and the reference population. The "effective migration rate" is defined as m_e = deltau / Deltau. It can be calculated from the migration matrix L, whose entries L_ij give the number of genes from i which are found in j after migration and L_ii is the (normalised) number of genes which remain in i, minus 1. The effectie migration rate m_e is found by solving the equation uVec L = deltauVec, where deltauVec is the row vector of fluxes into each population at equilibrium. The vector uVec is the (normalised) number of genes in each population.

- Consider two populations that are separated by a genetic barrier. Within each population, each genetic background is considered as a separate sub-population. The size of these sub-populations is maintained at an equilibrium by selection and migration. Alleles can flow between different sub-populations in the same background by migration. The flux will therefore not only be determined by physical migration, but also on the relative abundance of the two genetic backgrounds in the two populations and the recombination rate.

- Bengtsson (1985) introduced the gene flow factor gff = m_e/m. BB1986 define b = 1/gff = m/m_e as the strength of a barrier to gene flow.

- Two situations are considered: i) two distinct populations which exchange migrants directly and ii) two genetically different populations meet in a one-dimensional habitat in which the population density is everywhere constant.

- In case ii) (one-dimensional habitat), Deltau is the difference in allele frequencies immediately to the left and right of the barrier. u' is defined as the gradient deltau/deltax (x is space) 'somewhat' to the left and right of the barrier. Then, the strength of the barrier is defined as B = Deltau/uPrime. It has the dimension of a distance and can be thought of as the length of unimpeded habitat that would present an equivalent obstacle to the flow of a neutral allele down a uniform gradient uPrime.

- BB1986 show that B can also be written as B = (sigma^2/2)(Deltau/deltau).

- The influence of the barrier on gene flow depends on the ratio B/sgima, where sigma is the standard deviation of the parent-offspring distance (Nagylaki, 1975). Introgression of neutral alleles across the barrier will be delayed for ~(B/sigma)2 generations (from Barton, 1979). However, even slightly advantageous alleles will pass through a localised barrier vary rapidly (within ~ log((B/sigma)^2 pi s / 2)/2s generations if s >> (B/sigma){-2}). Such alleles are delayed for much lesst time than they would need to cross a length B of unimpeded habitat (!). Hence, although the effect of physical distance and of localised barrier on a neutral allele qre equivalent, simple physical distance is a much more effective obstacle to the spread of advantageous alleles than a localised genetical barrier.

